    "bin-mo-dcsum-0416": {
      "contentType": "text/plain",
      "text": "DISCHARGE SUMMARY 4/16/2026\nAdmission: 4/12/2026  Discharge: 4/16/2026 (4 days)\n\nDISCHARGE DIAGNOSIS: Acute pyelonephritis due to ESBL-producing E. coli.\n\nHPI: 74F hx recurrent UTIs, mechanical mitral valve on warfarin, T2DM (glargine + empagliflozin), CKD 3b presenting with fever 38.6, left flank pain, dysuria.\n\nHOSPITAL COURSE: Started empirically on ceftriaxone 4/12. Persistent fevers to 38.9 through hospital day 2. Urine culture finalized 4/14: E. coli >100k CFU/mL, ESBL PRODUCER — resistant to ceftriaxone, ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin, and TMP-SMX (patient also has SJS allergy to TMP-SMX); sensitive to meropenem, ertapenem, nitrofurantoin, fosfomycin. Switched to meropenem 1 g q12h (renally dosed) 4/14 with defervescence within 24h. Blood cultures x2 no growth. Renal US: no abscess or hydronephrosis. Infectious Disease consulted (Dr. Adeyemi, Schuylkill ID Associates) — see faxed consult letter. Warfarin continued without interruption; INR remained therapeutic (2.6–2.9).\n\nDISCHARGE PLAN: Ertapenem 500 mg IV daily x10 days via home infusion (OPAT, renally dosed) to complete 14-day course. ID follow-up in OPAT clinic.\n\nKEY RECOMMENDATION (ID): For FUTURE febrile UTI episodes, empiric CARBAPENEM pending cultures given ESBL history — standard empiric ceftriaxone is expected to fail. Avoid TMP-SMX (SJS). Nitrofurantoin inadequate for pyelonephritis and relatively contraindicated with eGFR ~34.\n\nDischarge Cr 1.6 (baseline 1.5–1.7). Urology referral placed for recurrent UTI evaluation."
    },
    "bin-mo-uronote-0521": {
      "contentType": "text/plain",
      "text": "UROLOGY CONSULTATION NOTE 5/21/2026\n\n74F referred after 4/2026 admission for ESBL E. coli pyelonephritis; four culture-positive UTIs since 10/2024.\n\nEVALUATION: Cystoscopy today — normal urethra and urothelium, no stone, mass, or stricture. Bladder scan post-void residual 180 mL (elevated) — incomplete emptying likely contributing to recurrence, possibly compounded by diabetic bladder dysfunction. Renal US from admission without structural abnormality.\n\nASSESSMENT/PLAN:\n1. Recurrent UTIs with elevated PVR — timed and double voiding regimen taught. Will recheck PVR in 3 months; discuss intermittent catheterization if persistently >200 mL.\n2. Antibiotic prophylaxis DEFERRED — poor options: TMP-SMX contraindicated (SJS), nitrofurantoin relatively contraindicated at eGFR 34 and would select resistance, fluoroquinolones already resistant. Agree with ID that future febrile episodes warrant empiric carbapenem pending cultures.\n3. On empagliflozin (SGLT2i) — glycosuria may contribute to UTI risk; deferred risk/benefit discussion to PCP and endocrine given renal protection benefit.\n4. Counseled on hydration and early presentation with fever given prosthetic valve."
    },
